Speaker 1: Oh, shit.

44
00:02:36,341 --> 00:02:37,940
Speaker 0: And Know Your Creators.

45
00:02:38,461 --> 00:02:41,580
Speaker 1: I hope people don't think it's a baseball panel about baseball manga.

46
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:45,040
Speaker 0: Oh my god, well the description will at least set them straight.

47
00:02:45,101 --> 00:02:46,899
Speaker 1: People don't read the description, they look at the title only.

48
00:02:47,180 --> 00:02:51,860
Speaker 0: See, the problem is, anyone who goes to a panel on baseball anime has already seen a lot of anime.

49
00:02:52,121 --> 00:02:52,271
Speaker 1: Exactly.

50
00:02:52,580 --> 00:02:55,720
Speaker 0: Not many people start on like Princess 9.

51
00:02:55,720 --> 00:02:56,097
Speaker 1: Exactly.

52
00:02:57,221 --> 00:03:00,160
Speaker 0: And we're doing Beyond Dungeons and Dragons.

53
00:03:00,480 --> 00:03:02,440
Speaker 1: Which has nothing to do with Otacon.

54
00:03:02,920 --> 00:03:09,475
Speaker 0: Except for the fact that the crossover between anime and video games and board games and all that stuff is effectively infinite at this point.

55
00:03:09,495 --> 00:03:11,560
Speaker 0: I mean, the Venn diagram is so close.

56
00:03:11,841 --> 00:03:12,081
Speaker 1: I know.

57
00:03:12,582 --> 00:03:13,885
Speaker 1: It's just saying.

58
00:03:14,366 --> 00:03:15,268
Speaker 1: It's so sad though.

59
00:03:15,308 --> 00:03:20,259
Speaker 1: It's like we go to this anime convention for Otaku Generation and we say, "Here's a bunch of

60
00:03:20,299 --> 00:03:20,540
Speaker 1: stuff."

61
00:03:20,580 --> 00:03:22,523
Speaker 1: And they say, "Yeah, we want the same old, same

62
00:03:22,664 --> 00:03:22,844
Speaker 1: old.".

63
00:03:23,024 --> 00:03:24,587
Speaker 1: It's like, "Really?

64
00:03:24,607 --> 00:03:31,519
Speaker 1: If I was a panel picker, I would never pick the same panel to repeat unless it was opening

65
00:03:31,559 --> 00:03:32,180
Speaker 1: ceremonies.".

66
00:03:32,380 --> 00:03:34,385
Speaker 0: See, Scott, I would say just the opposite.

67
00:03:34,405 --> 00:03:40,740
Speaker 0: There are certain panels or types of panels that at large conventions you pretty much need every year because so many people come every year.

68
00:03:40,740 --> 00:03:41,642
Speaker 0: There's so many new fans.

69
00:03:42,043 --> 00:03:49,020
Speaker 0: I mean, the panel that tells people who don't know what anime to watch, who just got into anime, what anime to watch is an important panel.

70
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:52,806
Speaker 0: The, you know, how to run an anime club panel is an important panel.

71
00:03:52,826 --> 00:03:59,840
Speaker 0: There's all these kind of basic panels that you pretty much have to run every year and you'll always have people who have never seen it and need to see it.

72
00:04:00,520 --> 00:04:03,539
Speaker 1: Yeah, but quite often those are the people who do not come to that panel.

73
00:04:03,980 --> 00:04:04,242
Speaker 0: They will.

74
00:04:04,282 --> 00:04:05,289
Speaker 0: I mean, look at Anime Boston.

75
00:04:05,309 --> 00:04:06,940
Speaker 0: How many people came to anime you should see?

76
00:04:07,281 --> 00:04:11,311
Speaker 1: That was a lot of people, but, you know, many of them had seen anime.

77
00:04:11,331 --> 00:04:14,580
Speaker 1: judging by, you know, about half the people there were, you know, grown in and...

78
00:04:14,780 --> 00:04:17,920
Speaker 0: See, while you say that, half the people there had never seen Cowboy Bebop.

79
00:04:18,339 --> 00:04:18,481
Speaker 1: I know.

80
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:19,262
Speaker 1: It's scary.

81
00:04:19,283 --> 00:04:22,011
Speaker 1: It's like half the people, like, knew it and half the people didn't know it.

82
00:04:22,031 --> 00:04:25,300
Speaker 1: And I really wondered, like, why the half the people who knew it were there.

83
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:28,269
Speaker 0: But even those people, they hadn't seen half the other stuff.

84
00:04:28,289 --> 00:04:31,159
Speaker 0: I don't think anyone, maybe like four people out of the 800 in that room...

85
00:04:31,540 --> 00:04:33,450
Speaker 1: Are we in that much of a minority?

86
00:04:33,691 --> 00:04:35,300
Speaker 1: Are we the only people who've seen the stuff?

87
00:04:35,601 --> 00:04:45,699
Speaker 0: Well, remember when there was that someone posted in a forum thread a list of, like, the 100 greatest anime, and I remember going through the list, I had seen, like, 96 of them all the way through, and I knew what 100 of them were.

88
00:04:46,561 --> 00:04:46,857
Speaker 0: Yeah.

89
00:04:48,663 --> 00:04:51,000
Speaker 0: It made me almost a little bit sad for myself.

90
00:04:51,080 --> 00:05:07,400
Speaker 1: Well, there's not, you know, it shows you that there's, you know, there's a lot of anime, but it's not really so much that it's like, you can never watch it all, but you can surmount it, you know, such that, you know, you have a sufficient knowledge of a great deal of the work.

91
00:05:07,800 --> 00:05:16,775
Speaker 1: It's like, you can never read all the books, but if you spent your life reading, like, sci-fi books, you could conquer enough of them, you know.

92
00:05:17,155 --> 00:05:20,020
Speaker 1: Someone giving you a list of the greatest ones is like, yeah, I got that.

93
00:05:20,401 --> 00:05:25,131
Speaker 0: But at least for OdaKan, for these sorts of panels, I have this feeling that we're gonna be running Anime.

94
00:05:25,151 --> 00:05:29,440
Speaker 0: You Should See and Know Your Creators in some capacity at most anime conventions that we attend from now on.

95
00:05:29,460 --> 00:05:37,580
Speaker 1: Well, even if you agree with the argument that those panels should be run at every convention, you know, over and over again, let's get someone else to run those and do something different.

96
00:05:37,720 --> 00:05:37,840
Speaker 0: Why?

97
00:05:37,941 --> 00:05:38,643
Speaker 0: I enjoy doing it.

98
00:05:38,683 --> 00:05:44,160
Speaker 0: Plus, we've changed it up every time, and we got Daryl Surratt, and I think he added a lot to Anime You Should See.

99
00:05:44,541 --> 00:05:51,100
Speaker 1: Yeah, but also, you know, he came from Florida, so I felt bad that if he came here and didn't do anything, that would be sort of like a waste of his trip.

100
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:51,901
Speaker 0: Yeah, he had a lot to do on his own.

101
00:05:51,921 --> 00:06:06,480
Speaker 0: I mean, we'll talk about the random awesomeness of that vile specter of Moe panel, but the other thing is that if you saw Anime You Should See at Anime Boston, do not come to see it at OdaKan.

102
00:06:06,580 --> 00:06:09,585
Speaker 0: It is going to be the exact same panel.

103
00:06:09,845 --> 00:06:11,507
Speaker 0: Like, exactly.

104
00:06:11,728 --> 00:06:13,450
Speaker 0: Anime for anime, almost word for word.

105
00:06:13,490 --> 00:06:14,472
Speaker 0: Just leave it be.

106
00:06:15,012 --> 00:06:20,160
Speaker 0: However, Know Your Creators is basically going to be completely different, so go ahead and go to that one.

107
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:27,834
Speaker 0: I say this primarily because every con we go to, Anime You Should See is like standing room only, like people lined up outside, they have to turn a bunch of people away.

108
00:06:27,854 --> 00:06:30,340
Speaker 0: Know Your Creators never fills the room.

109
00:06:30,880 --> 00:06:32,419
Speaker 1: Yeah, it's kinda sad.

110
00:06:34,321 --> 00:06:37,200
Speaker 1: Because really, Know Your Creators is the one that probably should get more people.

111
00:06:37,560 --> 00:06:40,200
Speaker 0: But in other OdaKan news, I do want to bring this up before we get...

112
00:06:40,240 --> 00:06:42,560
Speaker 1: Maybe we should change the name to Creators You Should Know.

113
00:06:43,281 --> 00:06:47,419
Speaker 0: I kinda want to change it to like, Six Grades or something about six, and then every time we do it...

114
00:06:47,783 --> 00:06:48,618
Speaker 1: Why do you pick six?

115
00:06:49,221 --> 00:06:50,980
Speaker 0: That way we can give ten minutes per creator.

116
00:06:51,360 --> 00:06:54,780
Speaker 1: I guess, but you're forgetting the time it takes for the intro and the outro.

117
00:06:55,161 --> 00:06:58,028
Speaker 0: Well, ten minutes per creator, but there's some overlap.

118
00:06:58,048 --> 00:07:02,699
Speaker 0: Like, if I do Oshii and Shiro, there's going to be about five minutes of overlap between the two.

119
00:07:03,943 --> 00:07:05,740
Speaker 0: Which leaves them with only fifteen minutes total.

120
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:15,140
Speaker 0: Yeah, but OdaKan, other news, OdaKan's coming up, you know, we said we're going to go, and they opened up the Artist Alley, as they always do.

121
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:24,040
Speaker 0: I don't know if it was a record this year, but I applied for the Geek Nights Artist Alley table within a couple hours of them announcing registration.

122
00:07:24,463 --> 00:07:26,838
Speaker 0: And I am so far down the waiting list that there's no point.

123
00:07:28,360 --> 00:07:33,760
Speaker 0: And this is a problem every year, and I can't blame OdaKan or any convention that has this problem, because what do you do?

124
00:07:33,820 --> 00:07:40,880
Speaker 0: You have a very limited supply of Artist Alley tables, and an order of magnitude more people who want Artist Alley tables.

125
00:07:41,541 --> 00:07:48,320
Speaker 0: And any method you come up with to decide who gets them and who doesn't is going to be unfair to someone as opposed to someone else.

126
00:07:48,722 --> 00:07:50,820
Speaker 0: Or is going to cause some problem over another problem.

127
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:56,420
Speaker 1: One thing I would like to say, right, is that the room the Artist Alley is in is a very large room, yes?

128
00:07:57,301 --> 00:08:01,740
Speaker 1: There is a significant portion of that room that is relatively empty.

129
00:08:02,240 --> 00:08:05,520
Speaker 0: I think part of it is that there are rules about how much of the room can be filled with stuff.

130
00:08:05,940 --> 00:08:08,899
Speaker 1: I agree that there are rules about how much of the room can be filled with stuff.

131
00:08:09,380 --> 00:08:16,760
Speaker 1: However, I would also like to point out they have that area that is like, I guess, nominally for CCGs that no one uses at all.

132
00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:19,420
Speaker 1: And everyone just uses it to eat lunch, right?

133
00:08:19,501 --> 00:08:20,829
Speaker 0: Here's how I feel about that area.

134
00:08:20,850 --> 00:08:22,380
Speaker 0: The New York Anime Festival has it right.

135
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:25,259
Speaker 0: They just turned it into a maid cafe and didn't even pretend.

136
00:08:26,300 --> 00:08:31,540
Speaker 0: Or what OdaKan can do, either drop the tabletop gaming or get us to run it.

137
00:08:32,601 --> 00:08:32,802
Speaker 1: Right.

138
00:08:33,001 --> 00:08:37,640
Speaker 1: Either make that a real area and beef it up or turn it into Artist Alley tables.

139
00:08:37,960 --> 00:08:43,500
Speaker 1: And two, right, the art show really has not held up so much.

140
00:08:43,780 --> 00:08:45,195
Speaker 1: And I think, you know...

141
00:08:45,660 --> 00:08:47,713
Speaker 0: Wait, wait, are you proposing to get rid of the art show?

142
00:08:47,754 --> 00:08:48,660
Speaker 0: Because it always fills up.

143
00:08:49,284 --> 00:08:51,620
Speaker 1: I am proposing they reduce the art show slightly.

144
00:08:51,940 --> 00:08:52,193
Speaker 0: How so?

145
00:08:53,161 --> 00:08:58,200
Speaker 1: By reducing the available space and, you know, having some sort of quality filtration.

146
00:08:58,501 --> 00:08:59,852
Speaker 0: See, that's the problem.

147
00:08:59,932 --> 00:09:00,699
Speaker 0: Quality filtration.

148
00:09:01,340 --> 00:09:05,040
Speaker 1: There are always a few empty things, you know, that no one hangs up on.

149
00:09:05,240 --> 00:09:05,882
Speaker 0: Why even bother?

150
00:09:05,922 --> 00:09:12,480
Speaker 0: Because the amount of space you'll save by cutting like four of those partitions out of there is not going to affect anything else in that room at all.

151
00:09:13,142 --> 00:09:19,500
Speaker 0: There is no way to reduce the art show enough to make an impact without ruining the art show.

152
00:09:19,741 --> 00:09:21,270
Speaker 0: And you'll just make more people unhappy.

153
00:09:21,290 --> 00:09:22,779
Speaker 0: The art show, I think, should stay the way it is.

154
00:09:23,420 --> 00:09:32,520
Speaker 1: Also, I've heard complaints from artists who put things in the art show about the... They made a change to the way, you know, the finances of the art show for artists.

155
00:09:32,862 --> 00:09:35,680
Speaker 1: And it's actually a very bad deal for the artists.

156
00:09:35,901 --> 00:09:39,360
Speaker 1: Unless you can sell something that's really good for a large amount of money.

157
00:09:39,480 --> 00:09:40,579
Speaker 1: So I think the art show...

158
00:09:41,160 --> 00:09:41,918
Speaker 0: What were the changes?

159
00:09:42,642 --> 00:09:45,100
Speaker 1: I forget exactly, but many artists were complaining.

160
00:09:46,020 --> 00:09:46,515
Speaker 0: Yes, but Scott...

161
00:09:46,660 --> 00:09:50,100
Speaker 1: Basically, it's not worth it financially unless you sell something for a shit ton of money.

162
00:09:50,180 --> 00:09:57,820
Speaker 1: In which case, if they want to keep that financial arrangement, they should pretty much only allow things that are going to sell for a shit ton of money.

163
00:09:58,060 --> 00:09:59,873
Speaker 0: Wait, but Scott, I mean, what are even the changes?

164
00:09:59,933 --> 00:10:00,880
Speaker 0: You don't even know.

165
00:10:01,020 --> 00:10:04,860
Speaker 0: And how often do the artists at like an artist's alley or something complain about nothing violently?

166
00:10:05,240 --> 00:10:07,220
Speaker 1: Well, Nuri was complaining, so I trust what she said.

167
00:10:07,400 --> 00:10:08,344
Speaker 0: Alright, well, I'll look it up.

168
00:10:08,365 --> 00:10:11,640
Speaker 0: if you're going to bring this up without any references or citations other than hearsay.

169
00:10:12,022 --> 00:10:12,808
Speaker 1: It's not hearsay.

170
00:10:12,828 --> 00:10:14,520
Speaker 1: I'm referencing a person who complained.

171
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:15,326
Speaker 0: Yes, that's hearsay.

172
00:10:15,346 --> 00:10:16,799
Speaker 0: That's the definition of hearsay.

173
00:10:17,640 --> 00:10:18,860
Speaker 1: They changed something anyway.

174
00:10:19,980 --> 00:10:23,720
Speaker 0: Regardless, even if you cut it in half, that'll have no impact on any other part of the room.

175
00:10:23,840 --> 00:10:26,653
Speaker 1: Well, the whole area behind the art show is always empty.

176
00:10:26,834 --> 00:10:28,040
Speaker 1: Like, just a big empty space.

177
00:10:29,320 --> 00:10:30,896
Speaker 0: But if it's empty anyway, then you could...

178
00:10:31,445 --> 00:10:32,019
Speaker 1: Fill it with tables.

179
00:10:32,481 --> 00:10:33,760
Speaker 0: No, you can't most likely.

180
00:10:34,380 --> 00:10:34,899
Speaker 1: Yeah, they should.

181
00:10:35,160 --> 00:10:36,179
Speaker 1: They probably can't.

182
00:10:36,300 --> 00:10:36,778
Speaker 1: Find a way.

183
00:10:37,161 --> 00:10:39,380
Speaker 1: At the very least, you could spread out the existing tables.

184
00:10:39,862 --> 00:10:48,960
Speaker 0: No, the problem I realized, I didn't think of until recently, was that doing it the way they do... I mean, there's no safe or fair way to dole out the artist's alley tables.

185
00:10:49,380 --> 00:10:53,020
Speaker 0: But doing it first come, first serve, I'm starting to feel, is the worst possible way.

186
00:10:53,201 --> 00:10:54,198
Speaker 1: It is the worst possible way.

187
00:10:54,660 --> 00:10:57,720
Speaker 0: Not because it rewards the most obsessive people or anything like that.

188
00:10:57,840 --> 00:11:02,220
Speaker 0: Because that probably is better than just giving it out randomly to reward the people who care the most.

189
00:11:02,880 --> 00:11:07,960
Speaker 0: The problem is that it doesn't necessarily reward the people who care the most.

190
00:11:08,441 --> 00:11:21,320
Speaker 0: It basically will create this sort of meme propagation to where as soon as one person in a group of friends gets a table, they have called all of their friends on the phone immediately, and those people have all gotten tables.

191
00:11:21,680 --> 00:11:29,780
Speaker 0: So the people who start getting tables, the people who find out that it opened and get the first submissions in, are all friends with each other in this long chain of friendship.

192
00:11:30,340 --> 00:11:35,760
Speaker 1: Well, there might be a few trees, because anyone who discovers it on their own quickly enough is like a beginning node.

193
00:11:36,001 --> 00:11:45,660
Speaker 0: Yeah, but the point remains that you'll have generally very strong lineages of people that are all related to each other, and you'll kind of get a lot of samey-ness in the artist's alley as a result.

194
00:11:46,180 --> 00:11:48,899
Speaker 1: Well, the artist's alley at all the conventions have been very samey.

195
00:11:49,602 --> 00:11:51,700
